59r|t}} (born August 18, 1953) is an American politician who currently serves as the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] from [[Texas]]' [[Texas's 1st congressional district|1st congressional district]], in office since 2005. A member of the  [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]], Gohmert is part of the [[Tea Party movement]]. In January 2015, he unsuccessfully challenged [[John Boehner]] for the position of [[Speaker of the House of Representatives (United States)|Speaker of the House of Representatives]].<ref name=boehnerchallenge>{{cite web |url=https://www.dallasnews.com/news/politics/2015/01/04/texas-tea-partier-louie-gohmert-to-challenge-speaker-john-boehner|title=Texas tea partier Louie Gohmert to challenge Speaker John Boehner|date=January 4, 2015|accessdate=January 4, 2015|website=Trail Blazers Blog |publisher=The Dallas Morning News|last=Gillman|first=Todd J.}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nGohmert was born in [[Pittsburg, Texas]], the son of Erma Sue (n\u00e9e Brooks) and Louis Buller Gohmert. He is of German descent on his father's side.<ref name=frpg1>{{cite web|url=http://freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~battle/reps/gohmert.htm|title=Louis Buller \"Louie\" Gohmert, Jr.|publisher=ancestry.com|date=April 8, 2013|access-date=April 9, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100113111815/http://freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~battle/reps/gohmert.htm|archive-date=January 13, 2010|dead-url=yes|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rollcall.com/members/19262.html|title=Rep. Louie Gohmert (R-Texas)|publisher=rollcall.com|date=April 8, 2013}}</ref> Gohmert was raised in [[Mount Pleasant, Texas]], where he graduated from [[Mount Pleasant High School (Texas)|the local high school]] in 1971.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://projects.washingtonpost.com/congress/members/G000552|title=The U.S. Congress Votes Data Base: Louie Gohmert (R-TX)|publisher=washingtonpost.com}}</ref> He then enrolled in [[Texas A&M University]], receiving a [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]] in [[history]] in 1975.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/elections/2004/candidates/22273|title=Louie B. Gohmert (R)|publisher=washingtonpost.com|date=June 30, 2004}}</ref> While at Texas A&M, Gohmert was a student leader for the [[MSC Student Conference on National Affairs]] alongside future fellow Congressman [[Chet Edwards]], and a member of the [[Ross Volunteer Company]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://corpsofcadets.org/rva/|title=Ross Volunteer Association|website=Texas Aggie Corps of Cadets Association|language=en-US|access-date=2018-06-07}}</ref>\n\nGomert received a [[United States Army|U.S. Army]] scholarship while at Texas A&M, where he was a brigade commander of the [[Texas A&M University Corps of Cadets|Corps of Cadets]] and class president.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationaljournal.com/almanac/2010/memberdistrict/188|title=NationalJournalAlmanac Texas District 1 Rep. Louie Gohmert (R)|publisher=nationaljournal.com|date=April 8, 2013}}</ref>\n\nHe later received a [[Juris Doctor]] degree from [[Baylor Law School]] in [[Waco, Texas]] in 1977, where he was also class president.<ref name=\"The Wall Street Journal\">{{cite news|url=http://projects.wsj.com/campaign2012/candidates/view/louie-gohmert--TX-H|title=Louie Gohmert (R)|author=Staff|publisher=wsj.com}}</ref>\n\n==Early political career==\nGohmert served in the [[United States Army]] [[Judge Advocate General's Corps, United States Army|Judge Advocate General's Corps]], at [[Fort Benning, Georgia]], from 1978-82.<ref name=\"Houston Chronicle\">{{cite web|url=http://blog.chron.com/txpotomac/2010/07/texas-delegation-in-depth-louie-gohmert|title=Texas delegation in depth: Louie Gohmert|author=''[[Houston Chronicle]]''|publisher=chron.com|date=July 1, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"AUSA2011\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ausa.org/legislation/congressionalinfo/Documents/OAS%20112th%20Congress.pdf|title=Once a Soldier... Always a Soldier|author=Staff|year=2011|work=Legislative Agenda|publisher=[[Association of the United States Army]]|accessdate=January 26, 2013|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131021200011/http://www.ausa.org/legislation/congressionalinfo/Documents/OAS%20112th%20Congress.pdf|archivedate=October 21, 2013 |df= }}</ref> The majority of his legal service in the U.S. Army was as a defense attorney.\n\nGohmert was elected as a state district judge for Texas's 7th Judicial District, serving [[Smith County, Texas|Smith County]] ([[Tyler, Texas]]) from 1992 to 2002. He was elected to three terms.<ref name=\"Houston Chronicle\"/> He first saw national recognition for a 1996 probation requirement where he ordered an [[H.I.V.]] positive man, who was convicted on [[motor vehicle theft]] charges, to seek the written consent from all future sexual partners on a court provided form notifying them of his H.I.V. status.<ref name=\"JRootTXTrib08262012\"/>\n\nThe order angered [[LGBT]] activists and civil libertarians.<ref name=\"JRootTXTrib08262012\">{{cite web|url=http://www.texastribune.org/2012/08/26/courting-controversy-works-gohmert|title=Courting Controversy Works for Louie Gohmert|author=Jay Root|publisher=''[[The Texas Tribune]]''|date=August 26, 2012}}</ref> In 2002, Gohmert was appointed by [[Governor of Texas|Texas Governor]] [[Rick Perry]] to fill a vacancy as Chief Justice on Texas's 12th Court of Appeals, where he served a six-month term, which ended in 2003.<ref name=\"The Wall Street Journal\"/>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n{{more citations needed|section|date=May 2017}}\n\n===Elections===\nA mid-decade redistricting made the 1st District significantly more conservative than its predecessor. Tyler, which had long anchored the 4th District, was shifted to the 1st District. In the 2004 Republican primary, Gohmert defeated [[Texas House of Representatives|State Representative]] [[Wayne Christian]] of [[Center, Texas]]. He defeated [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] incumbent 1st District Congressman [[Max Sandlin]] with 61 percent of the vote. Gohmert has never faced another contest even that close, the lowest percentage of victory being 68 percent in the 2006 election.{{citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\n===Tenure===\n[[File:David Dykes Invocation Photo Op.jpg|thumb|R-L: House Chaplain\n[[Daniel P. Coughlin]] presents pastor [[David O. Dykes|David Dykes]] a certificate in honor of his September 10, 2008 Invocation of the US House, while Gohmert and Speaker [[Nancy Pelosi]] stand by.]]\n[[File:President George W Bush delivers remarks before signing the FISA Amendments Act of 2008.jpg|thumb|right|Gohmert watches [[President of the United States|President]] [[George W. Bush]] deliver remarks before signing the [[Foreign Intelligence Surveillance Act of 1978 Amendments Act of 2008|FISA Amendments Act of 2008]]]]\nOn July 29, 2009, Gohmert signed on as a co-sponsor of the defeated [[H.R. 1503]]. This bill would have amended \"the Federal Election Campaign Act of 1971 to require the principal campaign committee of a candidate for election to the office of president to include with the committee's statement of organization a copy of the candidate's birth certificate, together with such other documentation as may be necessary to establish that the candidate meets the qualifications for eligibility to the office of president under the Constitution\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.opencongress.org/bill/111-h1503/text|title=Text of H.R.1503 as Introduced in House: Presidential Eligibility Act&nbsp;\u2013 U.S. Congress|publisher=OpenCongress|date=March 12, 2009|accessdate=September 2, 2010|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110225200832/http://www.opencongress.org/bill/111-h1503/text|archivedate=February 25, 2011|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nGohmert stated in a House Judiciary Hearing on May 15, 2013, that he believed the FBI did not act with due diligence concerning alleged bomber [[Tamerlan Tsarnaev]]. His contention was that the FBI was more interested in Christian groups such as those led by [[Billy Graham|Billy]] and [[Franklin Graham]] than in groups that might be considered less politically correct to target. Attorney General [[Eric Holder]] responded to his claims: \"The only observation I was going to make is that you state as a matter of fact what the FBI did and did not do. Unless somebody has done something inappropriate, you don't have access to the FBI files ... I know what the FBI did. You cannot know what I know. That's all\". Gohmert objected to this on the grounds that Holder had \"challenge[d]\" his character and made several unsuccessful attempts to inject his viewpoint as a point of personal privilege.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/blogs/itsallpolitics/2014/04/08/300612766/holder-plays-asparagus-card-against-gop-antagonist|title=Louie Gohmert Goes Off On Eric Holder At House Hearing|publisher=NPR|date=April 8, 2014|accessdate=August 25, 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn January 3, 2013, Gohmert broke ranks with the House leadership to nominate outspoken Florida Representative [[Allen West (politician)|Allen West]] for [[Speaker of the United States House of Representatives|Speaker of the House]], although West narrowly lost his bid for re-election in November 2012, and was no longer a member of Congress.<ref>Chris Moody (January 3, 2013), [https://news.yahoo.com/blogs/ticket/john-boehner-elected-speaker-house-190301689--politics.html \"John Boehner re-elected as speaker of the House\"], yahoo.com; accessed August 24, 2014.</ref>\n\nAlthough he has previously ruled out the possibility of a bid for the U.S. Senate, he has recently been boosted by at least one \"tea party\" group (Grassroots America We the People) as a primary challenger to current Republican Senator [[John Cornyn]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Texas Tea Partyers want Louie Gohmert for Senate|author=Rayfield, J.|url=http://www.salon.com/2013/08/08/texas_tea_partiers_want_louie_gohmert_for_senate/singleton|newspaper=Salon|date=August 8, 2013|accessdate=August 9, 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn January 4, 2015, Gohmert announced he would formally challenge Speaker [[John Boehner]] for the Speaker of the House position in the [[Speaker of the United States House of Representatives election, January 2015|2015 election]]. He announced the move on ''[[Fox & Friends Weekend]]''. He lost to Boehner two days later, on January 6.<ref name=boehnerchallenge/><ref>{{cite web|last1=Kusma|first1=Tyler|title=Louie Gohmert Announces Challenge to Speaker John Boehner|url=http://tknn.info/TKNN/politics/congress/2015/01/04/louie-gohmert-announces-challenge-to-speaker-john-boehner|website=TKNN.info|publisher=TKNN|accessdate=January 6, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2015, Gohmert delivered a speech to the U.S. Congress in which he called upon the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] to disband due to its historical support of slavery and racism.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gohmert.house.gov/news/documentsingle.aspx?DocumentID=398237|title=GOP Rep. Gohmert: Democrats Should Change Their Name over Slavery, Racist History|date=July 10, 2015|website=Louie Gohmert}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zgRvVp8wmhk|title=Democrats Should Change Their Name|date=July 14, 2015|via=YouTube}}</ref>\n\nGohmert expressed fear that he might become the target of gun violence similar to that experienced by former Congresswoman [[Gabrielle Giffords]] and refused to hold public town hall meetings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/house/320778-gop-rep-invokes-giffords-shooting-as-reason-not-to-hold-town-hall|title=GOP Rep Invokes Giffords Shooting as Reason Not to Hold Town Hall|date=February 23, 2017|publisher=The Hill|accessdate=February 23, 2017}}</ref>\n\n====Fiscal policy====\nGohmert has signed the [[Taxpayer Protection Pledge|Americans for Tax Reform]]'s [[Taxpayer Protection Pledge]].<ref name=\"ATR\">{{cite web|title=The Taxpayer Protection Pledge Signers 112th Congressional List|url=http://s3.amazonaws.com/atrfiles/files/files/091411-federalpledgesigners.pdf|publisher=Americans for Tax Reform|accessdate=November 30, 2011}}</ref> He offered an alternative plan to kick-start the economy with his tax holiday bill that would allow taxpayers to be exempt for two months from having federal income tax taken out of their paychecks.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,459525,00.html|work=Fox News|title=Rep. Louie Gohmert Wants Congress to Ditch Federal Income tax for 2008|date=December 1, 2008}}</ref>\n\nHe was one of a number of Republicans who voted against the [[Budget Control Act of 2011]] on grounds it did not do enough to deal with the government's growing debt.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thepoliticalguide.com/rep_bios.php?rep_id=31558116&category=views&id=140971302572|title=Louie Gohmert: Debt, Deficit, Spending, and the Size of Government|publisher=The Political Guide|accessdate=April 13, 2012}}</ref>\n\nGohmert was one of four Republicans who voted against, joining 161 Democrats to oppose a balanced budget Constitutional amendment in November 2011.<ref>{{cite news|title=House rejects balanced budget amendment|agency=Associated Press|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/news/washington/story/2011-11-18/balanced-budget-amendment-house-vote/51297960/1|newspaper=USA Today|date=November 18, 2011|accessdate=December 30, 2012}}</ref>\n\nGohmert supports and voted for legislation in favor of [[school voucher]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thepoliticalguide.com/rep_bios.php?rep_id=31558116&category=views&id=20100527128545|title=Louie Gohmert&nbsp;\u2013 Education|publisher=The Political Guide|accessdate=April 13, 2012}}</ref>\n\nGohmert strongly supported the [[Baseline Reform Act of 2013 (H.R. 1871; 113th Congress)]], a bill that would change the way in which discretionary [[Appropriations bill (United States)|appropriations]] for individual accounts are projected in CBO's [[Baseline (budgeting)|baseline]].<ref name=\"cbo1871\"/> Under H.R. 1871, projections of such spending would still be based on the current year's appropriations, but would not be adjusted for [[inflation]] going forward.<ref name=cbo1871>{{cite web|title=CBO \u2013 H.R. 1871|url=http://www.cbo.gov/publication/45212|publisher=Congressional Budget Office|accessdate=28 March 2014}}</ref> Gohmert said that \"conservatives have advocated for years that there should be no automatic spending increases in any federal department's budget ... that has been a trap so when we simply slow the rate of increase, we are accused of making draconian cuts.\"<ref name=GohmertPRMay9>{{cite web|title=Gohmert Praises Baseline Reform Act of 2013|url=http://gohmert.house.gov/news/documentsingle.aspx?DocumentID=333177|publisher=The Office of Congressman Louie Gohmert|accessdate=April 7, 2014|date=May 9, 2013}}</ref> He argued the legislation would make clearer \"what is an increase and what is a cut\", put the government in the same situation as American families (who do not get automatic increases), and help with the task of getting the debt under control.<ref name=\"GohmertPRMay9\"/>\n\n====Climate change and the environment====\nGohmert does not believe in manmade climate change, and has asserted that data supporting the theory is fraudulent.<ref name=politicalguide>{{cite web|title=Louie Gohmert on Energy and the Environment|url=http://www.thepoliticalguide.com/Profiles/House/Texas/Louie_Gohmert/Views/Energy_and_the_Environment|date=November 9, 2010|accessdate=September 5, 2017|work=The Political Guide|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180715094057/http://www.thepoliticalguide.com/Profiles/House/Texas/Louie_Gohmert/Views/Energy_and_the_Environment|archive-date=July 15, 2018|dead-url=yes|df=mdy-all}}</ref> He opposes cap-and-trade legislation, such as the one that was passed in the U.S. House when it was Democratic controlled, and supports expanding drilling, and exploration and drilling in Arctic National Wildlife Refuge (ANWR).<ref name=politicalguide/>\n\nIn an interview on the [[C-SPAN]] program ''[[Washington Journal]]'' on July 8, 2015 after [[Pope Francis]] issued his second encyclical ''[[Laudato si']]'', Gohmert said the Pope was incorrect in identifying [[climate change]] as a serious problem.<ref>{{cite news|date=July 10, 2015|title=Louis Gohmert's \"Dumb & Dumber\" philosophy of climate denial|first=Bob|last=Cesca|url=http://www.salon.com/2015/07/10/louis_gohmerts_dumb_dumber_philosophy_of_climate_denial|accessdate=August 29, 2017|magazine=[[Salon (website)|Salon]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Louie Gohmert: The pope is treating climate change deniers like Galileo \u2014 and it's Obama's fault|first=David|last=Edwards|date=July 8, 2015|accessdate=August 29, 2017|url=http://www.rawstory.com/2015/07/louie-gohmert-the-pope-is-treating-climate-change-deniers-like-galileo-and-its-obamas-fault|agency=[[The Raw Story]]}}</ref> Gohmert supported the U. S. withdrawal from the [[Paris Agreement]].<ref>{{cite press release|title=Gohmert on Trump's Decision to Withdraw From Paris Climate Accord|url=https://gohmert.house.gov/news/documentsingle.aspx?DocumentID=398512|first=Louie|last=Gohmert|date=June 1, 2017|accessdate=August 29, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn a 2012 meeting of the [[United States House Committee on Natural Resources|House Natural Resources Committee]], Gohmert stated his strong support of a [[Trans-Alaska Pipeline System|trans-Alaskan pipeline]], as a means for [[caribou]] to have more sex.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.adn.com/2012/02/07/2304478/texas-congressman-lectures-colleagues.html|title=Texas congressman lectures colleagues on caribou romance|publisher=Anchorage Daily News|date=February 7, 2012|accessdate=April 13, 2012|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120315020948/http://www.adn.com/2012/02/07/2304478/texas-congressman-lectures-colleagues.html|archivedate=March 15, 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/the-state-department-is-no-donald-trump/2012/02/07/gIQANuCkyQ_story.html|work=The Washington Post|first=Al|last=Kamen|title=The State Department is no Donald Trump|date=February 8, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Lushing|first=Dustin|url=http://www.newser.com/story/139284/things-congress-talks-about-caribou-sex.html|title=Things Congress Talks About: Caribou Sex&nbsp;\u2013 Texas' Louie Gohmert says Alaskan pipeline is hot date meet-up|publisher=Newser|date=February 8, 2012|accessdate=April 13, 2012}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Gohmert, \"When [the caribou] want to go on a date, they invite each other to head over to the pipeline. So [his] real concern now [is] ... if oil stops running through the pipeline ... do we need a study to see how adversely the caribou would be affected if that warm oil ever quit flowing?\" Gohmert's comments were not favorably received by the rest of the committee.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.inquisitr.com/192125/texas-republican-supports-pipeline-for-the-sake-of-caribou-sex|title=Texas Republican Supports Pipeline For The Sake Of Caribou Sex|publisher=The Inquisitr|date=February 8, 2012|accessdate=April 13, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/in-the-loop/post/louie-gohmert-best-caribou-wingman-ever/2012/02/07/gIQAIj2dwQ_blog.html|work=The Washington Post|first=Emily|last=Heil|title=Louie Gohmert: Best caribou wingman ever|date=February 7, 2012}}</ref>\n\n====Social policy====\nGohmert has a pro-life voting record. He has stated that he believes that life begins at conception. Gohmert sponsored the Sanctity of Human Life Act. Gohmert voted for the Child Interstate Abortion Notification Act, a bill that prohibits the transportation of a minor across state lines for the purposes of an abortion without the consent of the minor's parents. He has 100% pro-life voting record rating from the [[NRLC]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ontheissues.org/TX/Louie_Gohmert.htm#Foreign_Policy|title=Louie Gohmert on Foreign Policy|publisher=OnTheIssues|accessdate=April 13, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thepoliticalguide.com/rep_bios.php?rep_id=31558116&category=views&id=20100506100929|title=Louie Gohmert&nbsp;\u2013 Abortion|publisher=The Political Guide|accessdate=April 13, 2012}}</ref>\n\nAt a congressional hearing on May 23, 2013, on an abortion bill that would ban the procedure after 20 weeks of pregnancy, Gohmert told the story of another couple he knew that decided to go through with their pregnancy despite learning of fetal anomalies. He told Zink, a woman witness, that she should have gone through with her pregnancy despite some doctor's opinion that the brain function was impaired, and then have a better assessment of the baby's health once it was born. Gohmert explained: \"Ms. Zink, having my great sympathy and empathy both, I still come back wondering, shouldn't we wait, like that couple did, and see if the child can survive before we decide to rip him apart? ... So these are ethical issues, they're moral issues, they're difficult issues, and the parents should certainly be consulted. But it just seems like, it's a more educated decision if the child is in front of you to make those decisions\", Gohmert said.<ref>{{cite news|title=Louie Gohmert Tells Woman She Should Have Carried Brain-Dead Fetus To Term, Just In Case (VIDEO)|author=Bassett, L.|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/05/24/louie-gohmert-abortion-ban_n_3332823.html|newspaper=Huffington Post|date=May 24, 2013|accessdate=June 24, 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn December 16, 2012, two days after the [[Sandy Hook Elementary School shooting|Sandy Hook shootings]], Gohmert appeared on [[Fox News Sunday]] and suggested that the tragedy would have never happened had the teachers been armed. He told host [[Chris Wallace (journalist)|Chris Wallace]], \"I wish to God that she [principal Dawn L. Hochsprung] had an [[M4 carbine|M4]] in her office, locked up so when she heard gunfire, she pulls it out... and takes him out and takes his head off before he can kill those precious kids.\" He claimed that the 20 victims who had been killed with a [[Bushmaster Firearms International|Bushmaster]] semi-automatic rifle had \"defensive wounds\".<ref>{{cite interview|last1=Lieberman|first1=J.|last2=Durbin|first2=D.|last3=Gohmert|first3=L.|interviewer=Wallace, C.|title=Connecticut school shooting reignites gun control debate; Gun policy|url=http://www.foxnews.com/on-air/fox-news-sunday-chris-wallace/2012/12/16/connecticut-school-shooting-reignites-gun-control-debate#p//v/2039381272001|type=Interview: News|work=Fox News Sunday|location=Washington, D. C.|date=December 16, 2012|accessdate=December 17, 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn March 22, 2016, Gohmert was one of only 4 representatives to vote against H.R. 4742 (383 voted for the act). H.R. 4742 is a bill to authorize the National Science Foundation to support entrepreneurial programs for women. Gohmert gave the following quotes in defense of his position: Gohmert acknowledged that the bill was \"well intentioned,\" but said that \"this program is designed to discriminate against that young, poverty-stricken boy and to encourage the girl. Forget the boy. Encourage the girl.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Gohmert|first=Louie|url=https://www.c-span.org/video/?c4587317/louie-gohmert|title=Clip of House Session of Rep. Louie Gohmert|type=video|date=March 22, 2016|access-date=February 9, 2017|publisher=[[C-Span]]}}</ref>\n\n====\"Terror baby\" national security vulnerability====\nOn August 12, 2010, Gohmert appeared on ''[[Anderson Cooper 360\u00b0]]'' to defend comments he had recently made on the floor of the House regarding \"terror babies\". In a speech about national security made on the House floor in June 2010,<ref>{{Cite news|last=Video|title=Original speech|newspaper=Youtube|date=August 14, 2010|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dorCLFVpzyo|accessdate=August 14, 2010}}</ref> Gohmert stated that a retired FBI agent had told him that one of the things the FBI had been looking at were terrorist cells overseas sending young women to become pregnant so they would deliver the baby in the United States, and then take the baby with them back to be raised as a terrorist. When adult, this operative\u2014a U.S. citizen by birth\u2014could be easily infiltrated in the U.S. to carry out terrorist actions.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/politics/texas-rep-louie-gohmert-warns-baby-making-terrorists-coming-article-1.182787|title=Texas Rep. Louie Gohmert warns of baby-making terrorists coming to US|publisher=nydailynews.com|date=June 27, 2010|location=New York}}</ref>\n\nOn ''[[Fox Business News]]'', Gohmert later claimed that an airline passenger with a relative in [[Hamas]] had a grandchild who was to be intentionally born in the United States.<ref>{{Cite news|title=... and avoid crackpot theories, too|newspaper=Boston Globe|date=August 14, 2010|url=http://www.boston.com/bostonglobe/editorial_opinion/editorials/articles/2010/08/14/and_avoid_crackpot_theories_too|accessdate=August 14, 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn the interview, Gohmert asserted that pregnant women from the Middle East are traveling to the US on tourist visas, planning to deliver the child there.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.texastribune.org/2010/06/28/tx-rep-louie-gohmert-warns-of-terrorist-babies|title=TX Rep. Louie Gohmert Warns of Terrorist Babies|author=Elise Hu|publisher=''[[The Texas Tribune]]''|date=June 28, 2010}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the [[Fourteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution]], this automatically grants citizenship to the child. He said that the child would then be returned to the mother's home country and be submitted to a life of terrorist training. Rep. Gohmert said he could not reveal the identity of the retired FBI agent who provided him the information, but he pointed out to a ''[[The Washington Post]]'' article,<ref>{{Citation|last1=Richburg|first1=Keith|title=For many pregnant Chinese, a U.S. passport for baby remains a powerful lure|newspaper=Washington Post|date=July 18, 2010|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/07/17/AR2010071701402.html|accessdate=August 13, 2010}}</ref> which described \"[[birth tourism]]\" packages, mainly directed at Chinese tourists. These \"birth tourism\" packages, Gohmert pointed out, take advantage of a \"gaping hole in the security of our country.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Cooper|first=Anderson|authorlink=Anderson Cooper|title=Video: Rep. Gohmert on 'terror babies' conspiracy |work=CNN|date=August 12, 2010|url=http://ac360.blogs.cnn.com/2010/08/12/video-rep-gohmert-on-terror-babies-conspiracy|accessdate=August 13, 2010}}</ref>\n\n====Letter to Director of National Intelligence====\nOn June 13, 2012, Gohmert was one of five Republican [[United States representative]]s (including [[Michele Bachmann]], [[Trent Franks]], [[Tom Rooney (politician)|Tom Rooney]], [[Lynn Westmoreland]]) to send letters to the Inspectors General<ref>{{cite web|url=http://media.cmgdigital.com/shared/news/documents/2012/07/18/ig_letter_odni.pdf|title=House Members Seek National Security Answers|date=June 13, 2012|publisher=Congress of the United States|accessdate=August 23, 2012}}</ref> of the Office of the Director of National Intelligence, the Department of Defense, the Department of Homeland Security, the Department of Justice and the Department of State outlining their \"serious national security concerns\", and asking for \"answers to questions regarding the [[Muslim Brotherhood]] and other radical groups' access to top Obama administration officials.\" In the letter, Gohmert and the other U.S. lawmakers wrote about information they claim \"raises serious questions about Department of State policies and activities that appear to be a result of influence operations conducted by individuals and organizations associated with the [[Muslim Brotherhood]].\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/blog-briefing-room/news/238721-bachmann-responds-to-mccain-speech-the-letter-is-being-distorted|title=House Members Letter|date=July 18, 2012|publisher=The Hill|accessdate=July 22, 2012}}</ref>\n\nOne of the letters in particular to Ambassador Harold W. Geisel, the Deputy [[Inspector General]] of the [[United States Department of State]], mentioned the Deputy [[Chief of Staff]] to [[Secretary of State]] [[Hillary Clinton]], [[Huma Abedin]], as an example of the undue influence. The letter said that Abedin, wife of former U.S. representative [[Anthony Weiner]], who had access to sensitive national security and policy information, \"has three family members\u2013her late father, her mother and her brother\u2013connected to Muslim Brotherhood operatives and/or organizations\", as backed up by a study by the [[Center for Security Policy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://s3.documentcloud.org/documents/402379/rep-michele-bachmann-correspondence.pdf|title=Letter to the Ambassador Harold W. Geisel|date=June 13, 2012|format=PDF|publisher=Congress of the United States|accessdate=July 19, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Cordes|first=Nancy|title=Michele Bachmann refuses to back down on claims about Huma Abedin|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-505267_162-57475483/michelle-bachmann-refuses-to-back-down-on-claims-about-huma-abedin|accessdate=July 19, 2012|newspaper=CBS This Morning|date=July 19, 2012|quote=Bachmann, from Minnesota, and the four other representatives sent letters to top intelligence and security officials last week warning that the Muslim Brotherhood, a global religious Islamic movement whose members have been linked to terrorist groups in the past, may have infiltrated the top levels of U.S. government.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://muslimbrotherhoodinamerica.com/key-findings|title=Key Findings|last=Gaffney|first=Frank|work=The Muslim Brotherhood in America|publisher=Center for Security Policy|accessdate=August 11, 2012|quote=Notably, six Islamist-sympathizers have achieved positions within or advisory roles serving Team Obama: Special Envoy to the Organization of Islamic Cooperation Rashad Hussein; Deputy Chief of Staff to Secretary of State Hillary Clinton [[Huma Abedin]]; Presidential advisor Dalia Mogahed; FBI Citizens Academy graduate Kifah Mustafa; Homeland Security Advisory Committee Member [[Mohamed Elibiary]] and Homeland Security Countering Violent Extremism Working Group Member Mohamed Magid.}}</ref>\n\nThe letter and the Center for Security Policy's accusation were widely denounced as a smear, and achieved \"near-universal condemnation\", including from several prominent Republicans such as [[John McCain]], [[John Boehner]], [[Scott Brown (politician)|Scott Brown]], and [[Marco Rubio]].<ref name= KayDailyBest2012>{{cite news|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2012/07/23/bachmann-gaffney-and-the-gop-s-anti-muslim-culture-of-conspiracy.html|title=Bachmann, Gaffney, and the GOP's Anti-Muslim Culture of Conspiracy |newspaper=[[The Daily Beast]]|author=[[Jonathan Kay|Kay, Jonathan]]|date=July 23, 2012}}</ref><ref name=SouthS>{{cite web|author=Sturgis, Sue|date=July 20, 2012|url=http://www.southernstudies.org/2012/07/meet-the-man-behind-the-muslim-conspiracy-uproar.html|title=Meet the man behind the Muslim conspiracy uproar|work=The [[Institute for Southern Studies]]|access-date=September 28, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150912044144/http://www.southernstudies.org/2012/07/meet-the-man-behind-the-muslim-conspiracy-uproar.html|archive-date=September 12, 2015|dead-url=yes|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author1=Bendery, Jennifer|author2=Terkel, Amanda|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/07/19/huma-abedin-michele-bachmann_n_1686557.html|publisher=The Huffington Post|title=More Republicans Speak Out Against Bachmann Attacks|date=July 19, 2012}}</ref>\n\nGohmert and his colleagues were praised by [[Newt Gingrich]] as the \"National Security Five\" in an editorial on the [[Politico]] website. Gingrich expressed he favors investigating the Muslim Brotherhood, and made clear his support to Gohmert and the other four state-elected representatives for rising up concerns that improve national security.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0712/79104.html|title=In defense of Michele Bachmann, Muslim Brotherhood probes|author=Gingrich, Newt|date=July 29, 2012|work=Opinion Contributor|publisher=Politico|accessdate=August 11, 2012|quote=The underlying driving force behind this desperate desire to stop unpleasant questions is the elite's fear that an honest discussion of radical Islamism will spin out of control. They fear if Americans fully understood how serious radical Islamists are, they would demand a more confrontational strategy.}}</ref> Columnist [[Cal Thomas]] replied, to accusations of \"McCarthyism\", that the real possibility of infiltration by Islamic extremists deserves to be investigated.<ref>{{cite news|title=Suppose Michele Bachmann is right?|first=Cal|last=Thomas|url=http://www.thestate.com/2012/07/29/2371334/thomas-suppose-michele-bachmann.html|newspaper=[[The State (newspaper)|The State]]|date=July 29, 2012|accessdate=August 11, 2012|quote=Like the ghosts of Shakespeare's Banquo or Dickens' Jacob Marley, the specter of the late commie-hunting congressman from Wisconsin, [[Joseph McCarthy]], will always be with us. It is summoned up today, by some on the left, who use it as a tool to thwart legitimate questions about people and ideologies that seek to destroy America.|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120811040903/http://www.thestate.com/2012/07/29/2371334/thomas-suppose-michele-bachmann.html|archivedate=August 11, 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n====Robert Mueller====\nRepresentative Gohmert was one of three [[Republican party of the United States|Republicans]] who called for the resignation of [[Robert Mueller]], the prosecutor investigating Russian interference in the 2016 presidential election, on the grounds that he can not conduct his investigation fairly because of his conduct as a prosecutor and as acting director of the FBI.<ref name=twsNewsy>Newsy, [http://start.att.net/player/article/newsy_now-3_house_republicans_call_mueller_compromised_deman-newsy#.Wf4nrLVISRI.facebook 3 House Republicans Call Mueller Compromised, Demand Resignation], Retrieved November 4, 2017, \"...Reps. Gaetz, Biggs and Gohmert think Mueller can't fairly conduct his Russia investigation because of events that happened while he was FBI director./..\"</ref><ref name=twsPolitico>Kyle Cheney, November 3, 2017, Politico, [https://www.politico.com/story/2017/11/03/house-republicans-robert-mueller-resignation-244517 Conservatives introduce measure demanding Mueller\u2019s resignation: It\u2019s the latest sign of GOP resistance to the special counsel\u2019s Russia probe.], Retrieved November 5, 2017</ref>\n\n==Reelection in 2016==\nGohmert handily won his seventh term in the general election held on November 8, 2016. With 192,434 votes (73.9 percent), he defeated the Democrat Shirley J. McKellar, who polled 62,847 ballots (24.1 percent).  [[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian]] Phil Gray polled 5,062 votes (1.9 percent).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://elections.sos.state.tx.us/elchist319_state.htm|title=Election Results|date=November 8, 2016|publisher=Texas Secretary of State|accessdate=December 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n'''[[United States House Committee on the Judiciary|Committee on the Judiciary]]'''\n* [[United States House Judiciary Subcommittee on the Constitution, Civil Rights, and Civil Liberties|Subcommittee on the Constitution and Civil Justice]]\n* [[United States House Judiciary Subcommittee on Crime, Terrorism, and Homeland Security|Subcommittee on Crime, Terrorism, Homeland Security, and Investigations]] (Vice Chair)\n'''[[United States House Committee on Natural Resources|Committee on Natural Resources]] (Vice Chair)'''\n* [[United States House Natural Resources Subcommittee on Energy and Mineral Resources|Subcommittee on Energy and Mineral Resources]]\n* Subcommittee on Oversight and Investigations\n\n===Caucus memberships===\n* [[Freedom Caucus]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.texastribune.org/2017/03/26/ted-poe-resigns-freedom-caucus/|title=U.S. Rep. Ted Poe resigns from Freedom Caucus|last=Livingston|first=Abby|date=2017-03-26|website=The Texas Tribune|access-date=2017-06-22}}</ref>\n* [[Israel Allies Caucus]]\n*[[United States Congressional International Conservation Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Our Members|author=|url=https://royce.house.gov/internationalconservation/members.html|format=|publisher=U.S. House of Representatives International Conservation Caucus |date=|accessdate=1 August 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Tea Party Caucus]]\n* [[Republican Study Committee]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gohmert.house.gov/legislation/caucusmembership.htm|title=Caucus Membership : U.S. Congressman Louie Gohmert|website=gohmert.house.gov|access-date=2017-06-22}}</ref>\n* [[Congressional NextGen 9-1-1 Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=http://www.ng911institute.org/about-the-congressional-nextgen-9-1-1-caucus|format=|publisher=Congressional NextGen 9-1-1 Caucus|date=|accessdate=11 June 2018}}</ref>\n*[[Congressional Western Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=https://westerncaucus.house.gov/about/membership.htm|format=|publisher=Congressional Western Caucus|date=|accessdate=27 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Electoral history==\n{{Election box begin|title=[[Texas's 1st congressional district|Texas's 1st congressional district election, 2004]]<ref name=electionresults>{{cite web|url=http://elections.sos.state.tx.us/elchist.exe|title=Certified Election Results|publisher=Texas Secretary of State|accessdate=June 30, 2013|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140109062336/http://elections.sos.state.tx.us/elchist.exe |archivedate=January 9, 2014}}</ref>}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|party=Republican Party (United States)|